summary.seg: This manuscript contains the so-called Corpus Hermeticum and Plotinus' Enneads. The Corpus Hermeticum is a collection of philosophical-theological treatises comprising elements of magic and astrology, traditionally ascribed to Hermes Trismegistus, identified with the Egyptian god Thoth. The Enneads are the collection of the works of the neoplatonist philosopher Plotinus, collected by his pupil Porphyry.

The manuscript was copied in the 16th century, probably around the 1550s, as the watermarks suggest, by the prolific scribe Camillo Zanetti, his father Bartolomeo, and another contemporary scribe in Italy, where the Zanettis were active.

support.material: f. [ii] Western paper. Watermarks: Gothic letter P surmounted by a quatrefoil ( 63 20 ) comparable (although with differences) to Piccard online Buchstabe P DE4500-PO-110862 , which is dated to 1537.

pp. 1-[478], ff. [iii]-[iv] Western paper, folded in folio. Watermarks: pp. 1-[294], 295-[296]/309-[310] Anchor in a circle surmounted by a five-point star, countermark TC with a clover ( 68 43 ), in the centre of the leaf, identical with Sosower Ancre 96 , which is dated to ca. 1550-1552.
pp. 297-[308], 311-[326] Justice with countermark BS with a clover ( 117 55 ), in the centre of the leaf, identical with Sosower Justice 2 , which is dated to 1556 (Rome).
pp. 327-[358] Letters
P3 with a clover ( 30 24 ), in the centre of the leaf, identical with Sosower Lettres assemblées 35 , which is dated to ca. 1549-1553.
pp. 359-[478], ff. [iii]-[iv] Anchor in a circle surmounted by a five-point star, countermark BE ( 64 42 ), in the centre of the leaf, identical with Sosower Ancre 49 , which is dated to ca. 1553.

foliation.p: Modern pencil pagination, in Arabic numerals, in the upper margin right, from 1 to 477. Numbers are present only on the recto of the leaves, with some cases of - mistakenly - foliated leaves, which resulted in the presence of pages indicated by a number and the letters a/b. Two leaves at the beginning and three at the end of the manuscript are unnumbered (ff. [i]-[ii], [iii]-[v]): ff. [i]-[ii] + pp. 1-[68], 69a, 69b, 70a, 70b, 71-[116], 117a, 117b, 118a, 118b, 119-[138], 139a, 139b, 140a, 140b, 141-[154], 155a, 155b, 156a, 156b, 157-[160], 161a, 161b, 162a, 162b, 163-[478] + ff. [iii]-[v].

collation.p: The manuscript consists of quaternions, except for the last quire, which is a ternion.
collation.catchwords: Vertical catchwords by the scribes, written from top down, in the lower margin of the last leaf of each quire, near the gutter. They are not present in the leaves where the text has been written by hand B ( pp. [314]-375).

supportDesc.condition: The manuscript is in good condition. There are passim some stains (see p. 65).

handNote.p: pp. 1-[62], 67-[314] l. 12 Hand A: Camillo Zanetti (16th c., first half-after 1587) Camillo Zanetti (16th c., first half-after 1587) ( RGK I, 212; on him also RGK II 299; RGK III, 351).
The text is written in brown ink; titles and initials in red.

pp. [314] l. 13-375 Hand B: another scribe took over from Camillo Zanetti on p. [314], in a minuscule script datable in the 16th c., slightly slanting to the right, regular in size, characterised by a tendency to use squared forms and to emphasize the oblique strokes.
The text is written in brown ink; titles and initials in red.
pp. [376]-477 Hand C: Bartolomeo Zanetti (1486/1487-1547 at least) Zanetti, Bartholomeo, 1486 or 1487- ( RGK I, 31; on him also RGK II 43; RGK III, 56).
The text is written in brown ink; titles and initials in red.

decoDesc.decoNote:
Various small friezes in red ink, characteristics of the production of Camillo Zanetti:
an undulated linear frieze with clovers at both ends on p. 1
an undulated linear frieze with a clover and a leaf at the ends pp. 53, 67-69a, 125, [286], [290].
Initials in ekthesis in red ink are decorated with a simple vegetal motif, see e.g. p. 1.

additions.p: On the left pastedown is glued a label with the shelfmark.

On f. [ii] recto there is an indication about the contents in the upper part of the leaf, In hoc volumine continentur | Hermes Trismegistus | Plotini Enneades. Below, by another hand, in black ink, is written a table of contents of the books of the Enneades as contained in the manuscript, with references to a printed edition.
In the upper margin of p. 1 is written the shelfmark B.9.9.

binding.p:
16th/17th century western full leather binding, pasteboards. Golden tooling on both covers: arms of Silvius Elwes (see History) in an oval, with particulars painted in red, and initials S. E. On spine, gold tooling on a red square with title Hermes | Trismegistius | et Plotini | Enneades and three paper labels with the shelfmark. The edges are coloured in blue/green.
345 250 68

origin.p: As the watermarks and the scripts indicate, the manuscript was copied around the 1550s-1560s by the scribe Camillo Zanetti, his father Bartolomeo, and another contemporary scribe, in Italy.

history.provenance: The manuscript was owned by Silvius Elwes (ca. 1576-1638) Silvius Elwes (ca. 1576-1638) , Chaplain of Trinity College.
history.acquisition: It was donated by Silvius Elwes Silvius Elwes (ca. 1576-1638) to Trinity College Library between 1626 and 1630 (see P. Gaskell, Trinity College Library: the first 150 years (Cambridge, 1980), p. 234). On the right margin, lower part, of p. 1 is pasted the Trinity College bookplate. On pp. 1, [62], 67 and 477 there are stamps of Trinity College Library.

recordHist.source: Description (2020) draws partly on M.R. James, The Western Manuscripts in the Library of Trinity College Cambridge (Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1900), vol. 1, p. 147.
